The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Friday, August 06, 2004  Business Briefs																								 New Delhi, Aug. 5: Finance minister P. Chidambaram today hinted at more changes in tax structure and phasing out of subsidies for the textile sector, while promising measures to facilitate additional investment of Rs 1,40,000 crore by 2010. All natural fibres are now free from excise duties, with the mandatory duty remaining only on man-made fibres. But given the direction in which I think taxation in this industry should go, you can guess where the next budget will take us and where budget after that will take us, he said. 																								 Mumbai, Aug. 5: Global Trust Bank (GTB) has appointed Verma and Verma Associates as its new auditor in place of M. P. Chitale and Associates. The Kochi-based accountancy firm will assess the asset and liabilities of GTB.																								 London, Aug. 5: Essel Propack, worlds largest manufacturer of laminated tubes, today acquired 100 per cent stake in Arista Tubes, UK, in a move to expand its plastic tube market in Europe.																								 New Delhi, Aug. 5: Hyundai Motor India today hiked prices of its various cars, including Santro and Sonata, by up to Rs 10,700 to pass on the 2 per cent education cess to its customers.																								 New Delhi, Aug. 5: Indian Airlines has got responses from four aircraft leasing or manufacturing firms for dry-lease of 11 A-319 planes for its wholly-owned subsidiary, Alliance Air, official sources said.
